ok i want to master Java , springboot , kafka ,GIT , jenkins , Docker, Kubernetes by using just hardwork category 1 
how to do it , how long does it take (not more than 3 months ) give me 25 topics in each skills and  steps to achive it

ou can make big progress in Java, Spring Boot, Kafka, Git, Jenkins, Docker & Kubernetes in 3 months with consistent, focused effort (Category 1 hard work = working hard every day, but sustainably). Whether you “master” them depends on your baseline, but you can reach a strong mid‐to‐high competency.

Here’s a plan + topic lists + steps to maximize learning in 3 months.

🎯 Plan Overview: 3‑Month Learning Strategy (Category 1 Hard Work)

You have ~90 days. To use them well:

Daily time: ~5‑6 hours/day minimum for learning + practice.

Weekly schedule: One main topic + small review + project practice.

Hands‑on: Build something, break it, debug, re‑build.

Review & revise: Every week revisit older topics.

Use tools: code, exercises, tutorials, docs, source code reading.

⚙️ Major Skills & Topic Lists

Here are 25 important subtopics for each technology. You don’t need to master all 25 deeply, but aim to cover them at least roughly, and some in depth.

1. Java

Basic syntax, data types, control flow (if, loops)

OOP: classes, objects, inheritance, interfaces, abstract classes

Exception handling (try/catch/finally, custom exceptions)

Collections framework (List, Set, Map, Queues)

Generics

Java 8 features: Lambdas, Streams, Optional

Concurrency – Threads, Runnable, ExecutorService, Futures

Synchronization, Locks, Volatile, Atomic types

I/O: File, Streams, NIO, serialization

JDBC / basic database connectivity

JVM internals: GC, memory model, heap vs stack, JIT

Class loading, reflection

Annotations, meta‑annotations, custom annotations

Java modules (JPMS) if needed

Designing vs code: SOLID principles, design patterns (Singleton, Factory, Observer etc.)

Testing: JUnit, mocking (Mockito)

Build tools: Maven or Gradle

Logging (SLF4J, Logback / Log4j)

Java versions & upgrades (knowing new features)

Performance tuning and profiling (heap dumps, thread dumps)

Security basics: input validation, encryption, hashing, secure coding

APIs: RESTful, JSON serialization/deserialization

Date/Time APIs (java.time)

Functional programming in Java (map/filter/reduce etc.)

Best practices, clean code and code readability.

2. Spring Boot

Spring Boot setup / project structure

Dependency Injection (DI), Auto wiring

Spring configuration (application.properties/yml)

Controller, Service, Repository layers

RESTful APIs

Spring Data JPA / ORM (using Hibernate)

Database migration (Liquibase / Flyway)

Validation (Bean Validation)

Exception Handling in Spring Boot (global handlers)

Security: Spring Security, JWT, OAuth2 basics

Testing: Integration tests, Unit tests with Spring Boot Test

Actuator (monitoring endpoints)

Logging and tracing

CORS, Filters, Interceptors

Caching (e.g., using Ehcache, Redis)

Scheduling tasks (cron jobs)

Profiles (dev, prod) and external config

Spring Boot starters and dependencies management

Asynchronous programming (async, @Async)

Messaging (with Kafka / RabbitMQ)

File upload/download, handling multipart requests

WebSockets / Server Sent Events (if needed)

Versioning REST APIs

Best practices, error handling, clean architecture

Deployment: packaging (jar/war), containerization.

3. Kafka

Kafka architecture: brokers, clusters, Zookeeper (if version uses it)

Topics and Partitions, Replication factor

Producers: writing messages, serializers

Consumers: reading messages, deserializers

Consumer groups, offsets, committing offsets

Partitioning strategy (how keys map)

Retention policies, log compaction vs deletion

Exactly once / at least once / at most once delivery semantics

Kafka Connect (source and sink connectors)

Kafka Streams API

Schema registry (Avro / Protobuf / JSON)

Message format and compression

Monitoring: metrics, lag, throughput, broker health

Fault tolerance: what happens when brokers die, leader election

Security: SSL/TLS, authentication, ACLs

Configuration tuning: batch sizes, linger, buffer memory etc.

Consumer partition rebalances, partition reassignment

Throughput vs latency trade‑offs

Kafka cluster setup: replication, under‑replicated partitions

Data serialization and backward/forward compatibility

Brokers vs clients version compatibility

Handling schema evolution

Producer/Consumer error handling, retries

Kafka for event sourcing or CQRS use cases

Deploying Kafka in Docker / Kubernetes for practice.

4. Git

Git basics: init, clone, commit, status

Branching and merging (feature branches, master, dev etc.)

Pull, push, fetch, remote repos

Rebasing vs merging

Conflict resolution

Tagging and releases

Working with .gitignore

Stashing, cherry‑pick, revert

Undoing changes (reset, checkout)

Branching strategies (GitFlow, trunk‑based)

Working with remote forks, pull requests

Hooks (pre‑commit, post‑commit)

Submodules / subtree (if needed)

Git configuration (user, aliases)

Git workflows in teams

History inspection: log, reflog, blame

Resolving merge conflicts, rebase conflicts

Performance: large repos, sparse checkout

Using GUI tools / IDE integration

Best practices for commit messages

Security: signing commits, preventing secrets in repos

Git for CI/CD pipelines

Rewriting history when needed (interactive rebase)

Managing binary / large files (Git LFS)

Backup / backup branches.

5. Jenkins

Jenkins installation and setup

Pipeline vs Freestyle jobs

Jenkinsfile (Declarative vs Scripted pipelines)

Plugins: use, updates, managing them

Build triggers (on commit, timer‑based, manual)

Integration with Git, GitHub / Bitbucket etc.

Building Java projects: Maven / Gradle integration

Running tests in builds; test reports & reports aggregation

Artifact management (store, versioning)

Handling credentials / secrets securely

Parallel builds / stages in pipeline

Parameterized builds

Build agents and distributed builds

Notifications (Slack/email etc.)

Build job chaining, dependencies

Environment variables and configuration

Handling failures and rollback strategies

Artifact deployment (to servers, docker registry)

Security configuration: users, roles, authorization

Backup of Jenkins, pipelines, jobs

Monitoring / logging of Jenkins

Blue-green / Canary deployment strategies via Jenkins

Integration with Docker / Kubernetes agents

Performance / optimizing build times

Maintaining Jenkins upgrades, backup.

6. Docker & Kubernetes (combined but split)

Docker topics:

What is a container vs VM

Docker architecture: Docker Daemon, client, engine

Docker images: building, layering, Dockerfile best practices

Container lifecycle (run, stop, remove etc.)

Volumes, Bind Mounts, Persistent storage

Networking: bridge, host, overlay networks

Docker Compose for multi‑container apps

Registries (Docker Hub / private registries)

Image optimization, caching, multistage builds

Security: image scanning, privileges, kernel namespaces etc.

Debugging containers, logs

Resource limits (CPU, memory)

Docker swarm (if needed) or alternatives

Health checks

EntryPoint vs CMD etc.

Multi‑arch images

Container restart policies

Environment variables and configuration inside containers

Docker on Mac/Linux/Windows differences

Storage drivers, overlayfs etc.

Handling secrets in containers

Container monitoring and logging

Using Docker in CI/CD pipelines

Cleanup of images / unused containers

Pulling/pushing images, securing registry.

Kubernetes topics:

Architecture: control plane (API server, etcd, scheduler), worker nodes etc.

Pods: single vs multi‑container, lifecycle

Deployments, ReplicaSets

Services: ClusterIP, NodePort, LoadBalancer

Namespaces

ConfigMaps & Secrets

Volumes & persistent storage (PVC, PV)

StatefulSets, DaemonSets, Jobs, CronJobs

Ingress and Ingress controllers

Networking: CNI, network policies, DNS within cluster

Scaling: Horizontal Pod Autoscaler, Vertical scaling, cluster autoscaler

Rolling updates & rollbacks

Scheduling: node affinity, taints and tolerations

Resource requests & limits

Monitoring & logging (Prometheus, Grafana etc.)

Health probes: liveness, readiness

Security: RBAC, PodSecurityPolicies / PodSecurityStandards, admission controllers

Custom Resource Definitions (CRDs) and Operators

Helm charts

Multi‑cluster / high availability setup

Storage classes, dynamic provisioning

Backup & disaster recovery

Service mesh basics (optional, e.g., Istio)

Observability & tracing

Upgrades & version compatibility, cluster maintenance.

🗓️ Suggested 3‑Month Schedule

Here is a suggested weekly plan. You may adjust depending on prior knowledge.

Week	Focus Technology	What to Learn / Do
1	Java basics + Git basics	Cover Java topics 1‑10 + Git topics 1‑5; start a small Java project; learn Git workflow
2	Java concurrency, testing + Git advanced	Java topics 11‑20; Git topics 6‑12; continue project, integrate version control
3	Spring Boot fundamentals	Spring Boot topics 1‑8; build simple REST APIs
4	Spring Boot advanced + integrate Java & Git	Spring Boot topics 9‑16; test, security, exception handling
5	Kafka basics	Kafka topics 1‑6; set up Kafka locally; simple producer/consumer
6	Kafka deeper + integrate with Spring Boot	Kafka topics 7‑15; use schema registry, do a microservice app that produces/consumes
7	Docker basics	Docker topics 1‑10; containerize your Spring Boot & Kafka microservices
8	Docker compose & integration + Git/Jenkins basics	Docker topics 11‑20; Git workflows; start Jenkins basics, build pipelines for your containerized app
9	Kubernetes basics	K8s topics 1‑10; deploy your containers to local K8s (e.g., minikube / kind)
10	Kubernetes advanced + Jenkins pipelines + CI/CD	K8s topics 11‑20; Jenkins: pipelines, deployment via Jenkins to K8s
11	Polish: security, monitoring, observability	Fill in missing topics: security in all layers, monitoring Kafka, services, logging, alerting etc.
12	Final project + review + interview prep	Build end‑to‑end microservices app using all tech: Java + Spring Boot + Kafka + Docker + K8s, CI/CD with Jenkins, Git workflow. Review weak areas. Practice explaining / debugging.
🕒 Estimate of How Long It Takes

If you follow above plan with ~5‑6 hours/day:

Basic competence in each tech (Java, Spring Boot, Git) in ~4‑5 weeks.

Kafka + Docker + Kubernetes need hands‑on time; expect 2‑3 weeks each to build comfort.

Full integration + projects + polish + security + production‑style aspects mostly in last 4‑5 weeks.

So 3 months is tight but possible to reach solid competence, not “guru” level. Mastery (deep internals, heavy optimization) will take longer.

🧰 Tips to Get Most Out of Hard Work Level 1

Use small projects and gradually increase complexity. E.g., simple REST API → microservice → message passing with Kafka → dockerize → deploy to K8s.

Code every day. Even small tasks count.

Read official docs; try to read source code of frameworks when possible.

Get feedback — code reviews, posting on forums.

Make mistakes — break things, debug.

Keep a journal: what you learn each day; areas that were hard; revisit them.

Do spaced repetition: revisit old topics after a few weeks.

