GIT :

🟢 1. Core Concepts (Beginner)

These are the fundamentals. Without these, Git is frustrating.

✅ Repositories (git init, git clone)

✅ Staging and committing (git add, git commit)

✅ Branches (git branch, git checkout, git switch)

✅ Merging (git merge)

✅ Status & logs (git status, git log)

✅ Remote repositories (git remote, git push, git pull, git fetch)

✅ Basic .gitignore

🟡 2. Daily Workflow Commands (Intermediate)

For effective daily usage and avoiding common mistakes.

✅ git stash — temporarily save changes

✅ git diff — see what changed

✅ git reset (soft, mixed, hard) — undo things

✅ git restore — recover files or discard changes

✅ git rebase (interactive too) — clean up commit history

✅ git cherry-pick — apply a commit from one branch to another

✅ Tracking branches (--track, --set-upstream-to)

✅ Resolving merge conflicts

✅ Understanding HEAD, working directory, and staging area

🟠 3. Collaboration & Best Practices

How to work well in a team and avoid breaking stuff.

✅ Forking, Pull Requests (PRs) — on GitHub/GitLab

✅ Good commit messages (atomic, clear, meaningful)

✅ Git workflows: Git Flow, GitHub Flow, trunk-based development

✅ Rebasing vs Merging (and when to use each)

✅ Squash and rebase before merging (for clean history)

✅ Using tags and releases

✅ Protected branches & code reviews

🔴 4. Advanced Topics (Power User Level)

These give you true control and confidence in complex scenarios.

✅ Reflog (git reflog) — recover from "oh no!" mistakes

✅ Submodules & monorepos

✅ Hooks (e.g., pre-commit, pre-push)

✅ Bisect (git bisect) — find the commit that broke something

✅ Blame (git blame) — see who last changed a line

✅ Patch files (git format-patch, git apply)

✅ Worktrees — multiple working directories from the same repo

✅ Custom aliases (e.g., git lg, git undo)

✅ GPG commit signing

✅ Sparse checkouts (partial repo checkout)

🧠 Bonus: Understand the Git Internals (Optional but Powerful)

How Git stores data: objects, trees, commits, blobs

.git folder structure

How HEAD and refs work

Plumbing vs Porcelain commands

🔧 Tools to Pair with Git

GitHub CLI (gh)

Git GUIs: GitKraken, SourceTree, GitHub Desktop, VS Code Git integration

Diff/merge tools: Beyond Compare, Meld, KDiff3

CI/CD integration (GitHub Actions, GitLab CI)

📘 Resources to Learn

Pro Git book (free)

Git documentation: git help <command>

Online courses (e.g., Udemy, freeCodeCamp)

Practice sites: learngitbranching.js.org

✅ Final Tip

Don’t just memorize Git — practice in real or sandbox projects, break things, recover them, and build muscle memory. That’s how you really master Git.
